1
00:00:00,881 --> 00:00:07,826
[SPEAKER_08]: So this is the meeting of the Medford Historical Commission, Monday night, November 13th, 2023.

2
00:00:08,006 --> 00:00:16,132
[SPEAKER_08]: I'll call the meeting to order at 7.05 p.m., just gonna read the governor's statement.

3
00:00:17,313 --> 00:00:26,420
[SPEAKER_08]: On March 29th, Governor Healey signed into law a supplemental budget bill, which among other things, extended the temporary provisions pertaining to the open meeting law to March 31st, 2025.

4
00:00:28,461 --> 00:00:40,409
[SPEAKER_08]: Specifically, this further extension allows public bodies to continue holding meetings remotely without a quorum of the public body physically present at a meeting location and to provide adequate alternative access to remote meetings.

5
00:00:40,889 --> 00:00:49,635
[SPEAKER_08]: Language does not make any substantive change to the open meeting laws other than extending the expiration date of the temporary provisions regarding remote meetings from March 31st, 2023 to March 31st, 2025.

6
00:00:54,436 --> 00:00:58,762
[SPEAKER_08]: So for folks who want to join us in the future, you can log into the city's website.

7
00:00:58,902 --> 00:01:00,084
[SPEAKER_08]: Our agendas are posted there.

8
00:01:00,164 --> 00:01:01,906
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Dennis, for posting that.

9
00:01:01,946 --> 00:01:04,370
[SPEAKER_08]: We usually post the Wednesday before.

10
00:01:05,111 --> 00:01:07,153
[SPEAKER_08]: So we get all of our business in.

11
00:01:07,674 --> 00:01:08,015
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay.

12
00:01:12,093 --> 00:01:14,955
[SPEAKER_08]: On the agenda tonight, new business, 56 Wareham Street.

13
00:01:14,975 --> 00:01:21,379
[SPEAKER_08]: We're gonna receive the demolition application that we received two days after the previous meeting and make a determination of significance.

14
00:01:21,799 --> 00:01:24,761
[SPEAKER_08]: Commissioners, I sent around the link, it's on the Google Drive.

15
00:01:24,841 --> 00:01:30,104
[SPEAKER_08]: If I could have your acceptance of the demo application and then we'll go from there.

16
00:01:31,345 --> 00:01:33,406
[SPEAKER_01]: Motion to accept the demolition application.

17
00:01:33,426 --> 00:01:36,328
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you.

18
00:01:37,609 --> 00:01:38,049
[SPEAKER_09]: And a second.

19
00:01:38,069 --> 00:01:38,569
[SPEAKER_05]: Second.

20
00:01:39,030 --> 00:01:39,390
[SPEAKER_05]: Second.

21
00:01:41,063 --> 00:01:41,643
[SPEAKER_08]: seconded.

22
00:01:41,703 --> 00:01:42,743
[SPEAKER_08]: I'll go around the room.

23
00:01:42,783 --> 00:01:43,563
[SPEAKER_08]: Roll call vote.

24
00:01:44,044 --> 00:01:44,324
[SPEAKER_08]: Jen?

25
00:01:45,784 --> 00:01:46,044
[SPEAKER_09]: Yes.

26
00:01:46,524 --> 00:01:46,764
[SPEAKER_09]: Peter?

27
00:01:47,724 --> 00:01:48,004
[SPEAKER_09]: Yes.

28
00:01:48,564 --> 00:01:48,764
[SPEAKER_09]: Kit?

29
00:01:49,565 --> 00:01:49,805
[SPEAKER_09]: Yes.

30
00:01:50,245 --> 00:01:50,485
[SPEAKER_09]: Doug?

31
00:01:51,005 --> 00:01:51,245
[SPEAKER_09]: Yes.

32
00:01:51,665 --> 00:01:51,885
[SPEAKER_08]: Jess?

33
00:01:52,805 --> 00:01:53,065
[SPEAKER_09]: Yes.

34
00:01:53,945 --> 00:01:54,406
[SPEAKER_08]: And that's it.

35
00:01:54,626 --> 00:01:55,166
[SPEAKER_08]: That's everybody.

36
00:01:55,346 --> 00:01:56,006
[SPEAKER_08]: So it's approved.

37
00:01:56,186 --> 00:01:58,326
[SPEAKER_08]: Five to zero.

38
00:01:59,126 --> 00:02:02,427
[SPEAKER_08]: I'll take a motion to kick off discussion of determination of significance.

39
00:02:03,827 --> 00:02:07,588
[SPEAKER_00]: Motion to find 56 Wareham historically significant.

40
00:02:11,448 --> 00:02:11,988
[SPEAKER_09]: And a second.

41
00:02:14,090 --> 00:02:14,590
[SPEAKER_09]: I'll second.

42
00:02:14,610 --> 00:02:19,353
[SPEAKER_09]: All right, Jen, you've got the floor.

43
00:02:20,334 --> 00:02:22,215
[SPEAKER_00]: OK, thank you.

44
00:02:23,716 --> 00:02:30,320
[SPEAKER_00]: In reading the form B for me, I actually wasn't

45
00:02:33,166 --> 00:02:47,797
[SPEAKER_01]: I wasn't overly enthralled with the description of the house itself, or the narrative in terms of it being overly interesting and in either section, and I did look at the Google map.

46
00:02:50,099 --> 00:02:55,122
[SPEAKER_01]: I really wanted to just take a look at the streetscape to see how the property fit in.

47
00:02:55,562 --> 00:03:04,227
[SPEAKER_01]: Certainly, I think Wareham, we could probably all agree is a little bit of a mishmash of two families, single families, triple deckers, it's a little bit all over the place.

48
00:03:05,107 --> 00:03:20,199
[SPEAKER_01]: However, I do think it is significant based on the age alone of the property and we have such diminishing resources of pre-1900 buildings that I am going to vote for significance on this one.

49
00:03:24,142 --> 00:03:24,942
[SPEAKER_01]: And I will leave it at that.

50
00:03:25,323 --> 00:03:25,743
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

51
00:03:25,843 --> 00:03:26,043
[SPEAKER_03]: Great.

52
00:03:26,283 --> 00:03:27,885
[SPEAKER_03]: Kit, do you want to continue the conversation?

53
00:03:29,453 --> 00:03:38,061
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, I think Jen just said exactly what I was going to say, which is, you know, especially this, the stock of, well, two things.

54
00:03:38,141 --> 00:03:44,066
[SPEAKER_03]: First of all, sort of the landscape from the street, the streetscape.

55
00:03:45,092 --> 00:03:56,623
[SPEAKER_03]: And I recognize Wareham is a mishmash, but it's going to become an increasing mishmash if we actually don't take some steps to limit that.

56
00:03:57,424 --> 00:04:03,089
[SPEAKER_03]: And then the second thing is, I think there is such a diminishing stock of houses of this nature in the city.

57
00:04:03,109 --> 00:04:09,735
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, we can't just be tasked with preserving only the largest and most

58
00:04:10,796 --> 00:04:11,996
[SPEAKER_03]: sort of elegant homes.

59
00:04:12,156 --> 00:04:16,757
[SPEAKER_03]: I think that there is, you know, these are like the starter homes for the next generation.

60
00:04:21,638 --> 00:04:23,179
[SPEAKER_09]: Great.

61
00:04:23,859 --> 00:04:24,159
[SPEAKER_09]: Peter?

62
00:04:26,639 --> 00:04:34,101
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, I just walked down the street on Google Maps and I think I agree it is a mishmash.

63
00:04:35,061 --> 00:04:38,082
[SPEAKER_05]: It's one of the smaller homes on the street, I believe.

64
00:04:40,604 --> 00:04:42,225
[SPEAKER_05]: I think it's kind of a charming house.

65
00:04:44,506 --> 00:04:50,930
[SPEAKER_05]: So I think, and it does have some excellent detail, although not in great repair.

66
00:04:54,792 --> 00:05:05,518
[SPEAKER_05]: Seems to have pretty early siding, if maybe not the original siding, and it has some nice detail on the columns, on the front porch and stuff.

67
00:05:05,538 --> 00:05:08,780
[SPEAKER_05]: So I think it's worth a pause to consider.

68
00:05:09,960 --> 00:05:14,501
[SPEAKER_01]: Peter, how was the condition from the exterior since you walked by it?

69
00:05:14,601 --> 00:05:15,261
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm curious.

70
00:05:15,581 --> 00:05:18,562
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, I only walked by it on Google Maps.

71
00:05:18,722 --> 00:05:19,402
[SPEAKER_01]: Oh, sorry.

72
00:05:19,422 --> 00:05:20,702
[SPEAKER_01]: You said you didn't say that.

73
00:05:20,742 --> 00:05:21,502
[SPEAKER_01]: I apologize.

74
00:05:21,522 --> 00:05:22,282
[SPEAKER_05]: No worries.

75
00:05:22,782 --> 00:05:34,404
[SPEAKER_05]: But yeah, I mean, I'm just zooming in on this front porch here, and it does look like there's rot and stuff, but, you know, on the base of the columns and stuff.

76
00:05:34,484 --> 00:05:38,085
[SPEAKER_05]: But I mean, all in all, it's not in bad shape for

77
00:05:40,133 --> 00:05:42,794
[SPEAKER_05]: how old it is, has nice brick foundation and stuff.

78
00:05:42,814 --> 00:05:45,875
[SPEAKER_05]: So I think it's worth a pause.

79
00:05:46,395 --> 00:05:54,678
[SPEAKER_05]: Um, I think there are quite a few of these end houses around, maybe not on this street, but I don't know.

80
00:05:55,078 --> 00:06:08,683
[SPEAKER_05]: Um, I thought, and I, I kind of agree with the other two commissioners that I felt like it was, it was a pretty interesting story and design, but not like, um,

81
00:06:11,462 --> 00:06:15,644
[SPEAKER_05]: outstanding in its architectural or historic interest.

82
00:06:16,004 --> 00:06:19,386
[SPEAKER_05]: Kind of like a common house, I felt.

83
00:06:19,646 --> 00:06:23,528
[SPEAKER_06]: Anyway, that's all for me.

84
00:06:24,868 --> 00:06:25,369
[SPEAKER_09]: Great, thanks.

85
00:06:25,529 --> 00:06:25,809
[SPEAKER_06]: Doug?

86
00:06:27,710 --> 00:06:29,911
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, this one's a little tough.

87
00:06:30,171 --> 00:06:32,352
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm actually on the other side of this one.

88
00:06:33,112 --> 00:06:37,394
[SPEAKER_07]: I understand that I wouldn't, mishmash is a little negative term.

89
00:06:37,434 --> 00:06:40,476
[SPEAKER_07]: I guess I view eclectic because it's just, it seems like

90
00:06:41,925 --> 00:06:49,510
[SPEAKER_07]: Every decade of the last 15 is represented somewhere on that street, you know, which is not uncommon in South Medford, I think.

91
00:06:49,930 --> 00:06:51,391
[SPEAKER_07]: It's a lot of change.

92
00:06:53,692 --> 00:06:56,914
[SPEAKER_07]: But I couldn't, you know, I know this one's looking for a full tear now.

93
00:06:56,934 --> 00:06:59,756
[SPEAKER_07]: They're not looking to make it bigger, build on the foundations.

94
00:06:59,816 --> 00:07:09,822
[SPEAKER_07]: I think they're looking to tear it completely down and build two townhomes, which is, I haven't seen any drawings, so I can't judge on that, obviously, but I'm not a big fan of that.

95
00:07:11,615 --> 00:07:19,742
[SPEAKER_07]: This building is awful small, and I struggle to see how it rises to the level of being perfectly preserved.

96
00:07:19,782 --> 00:07:26,807
[SPEAKER_07]: I understand the pause is probably not a bad thing, so I'm not unhappy that the other commissioners are looking to kind of pause the process here.

97
00:07:26,867 --> 00:07:29,089
[SPEAKER_07]: But right now, I'm on the other side of this.

98
00:07:31,351 --> 00:07:31,631
[SPEAKER_09]: Thanks.

99
00:07:32,532 --> 00:07:32,712
[SPEAKER_09]: Jess?

100
00:07:35,024 --> 00:07:40,826
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, the form B says that, you know, the house retains original or early building fabric.

101
00:07:42,307 --> 00:07:55,051
[SPEAKER_04]: But it also doesn't recommend for listing in the National Register, or really seem to, I think, put forth an argument for preservation.

102
00:07:55,092 --> 00:07:56,292
[SPEAKER_09]: So I think I'm with Doug on this one.

103
00:08:02,280 --> 00:08:14,184
[SPEAKER_01]: I just wanted to say that I looked online to see if there were any interior photos and I didn't find any, not that that really matters, but I was more curious.

104
00:08:14,925 --> 00:08:24,929
[SPEAKER_01]: And that I think if just personally, if we were voting for preferably preserved status, I don't think I would vote to preserve it.

105
00:08:25,309 --> 00:08:27,370
[SPEAKER_01]: I do think it's worthy of significance.

106
00:08:28,662 --> 00:08:38,867
[SPEAKER_01]: But I also think that density in this neighborhood with the T nearby and whatnot might make more sense for the lot.

107
00:08:38,947 --> 00:08:46,971
[SPEAKER_01]: But I do think from a significant standpoint and it's pre-1900, for me, for right now, that's what I'm looking at.

108
00:08:47,031 --> 00:08:55,975
[SPEAKER_01]: I would be curious to hear if it goes to preferably preserved status and the public comes out, what would they think?

109
00:08:57,026 --> 00:09:18,778
[SPEAKER_08]: Right, I think I think that's the goal right so our job is to determine whether or not it's significant and then let the let the public decide with us whether it's in the interest of the city of Medford to save, you know, if all of a sudden, you know, somebody said oh we have a proposal to do to townhouses and they're going to be affordable or something like that that might be different than just simply maximizing the number of units that you can put on this lot.

110
00:09:20,619 --> 00:09:26,724
[SPEAKER_01]: This house reminds me of the little one on Cotting that we lost however many years ago.

111
00:09:27,085 --> 00:09:27,285
[SPEAKER_01]: Was it 15?

112
00:09:27,425 --> 00:09:31,509
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't think it was that long ago.

113
00:09:31,569 --> 00:09:33,331
[SPEAKER_08]: It might have been less than five years ago.

114
00:09:33,891 --> 00:09:36,274
[SPEAKER_01]: It was before COVID, which feels like 100 years ago.

115
00:09:36,294 --> 00:09:39,557
[SPEAKER_07]: Fifteen years or 15 street address?

116
00:09:39,917 --> 00:09:41,179
[SPEAKER_01]: No, I think it was 15 was the number.

117
00:09:44,176 --> 00:09:47,217
[SPEAKER_01]: Remember that little one, the worker's cottage?

118
00:09:47,617 --> 00:09:48,857
[SPEAKER_01]: It just reminded me of that.

119
00:09:50,938 --> 00:09:52,399
[SPEAKER_01]: Different neighborhood, though.

120
00:09:52,439 --> 00:10:02,142
[SPEAKER_07]: You raise a good point, Shannon, that it's the small in-houses that have the set kind of half-floor framing, that don't have a lot of headroom.

121
00:10:04,503 --> 00:10:07,684
[SPEAKER_07]: Unless it's an architectural gem, we tend to let those go.

122
00:10:07,704 --> 00:10:12,846
[SPEAKER_07]: And you're basically saying, we should think about that because then we'll have none left eventually.

123
00:10:12,886 --> 00:10:18,827
[SPEAKER_07]: And I don't know, Ryan, you seem to have these kind of factoids at your fingertips all the time.

124
00:10:18,847 --> 00:10:23,429
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, if you had to guess, do you think we have 10 of these houses, 50?

125
00:10:23,549 --> 00:10:25,990
[SPEAKER_07]: What are you thinking we have left of this type of building?

126
00:10:27,395 --> 00:10:31,121
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah, well let's let's start with the numbers right so there's less than 2000 3000 pre 1900 buildings of the city.

127
00:10:37,898 --> 00:10:45,744
[SPEAKER_08]: maybe let's just say on the safe side, like two dozen, three dozen, maybe good stick, this is a stick style house.

128
00:10:46,305 --> 00:10:49,747
[SPEAKER_08]: So it employs a number of architectural elements.

129
00:10:49,787 --> 00:10:54,111
[SPEAKER_08]: So it employs the knee wall construction that was popular from the 1850s onward.

130
00:10:55,051 --> 00:11:00,015
[SPEAKER_08]: But unlike the knee wall houses, this actually has a wider base.

131
00:11:00,476 --> 00:11:03,298
[SPEAKER_08]: And so as a result, it actually has a full third, like somewhat

132
00:11:03,478 --> 00:11:07,119
[SPEAKER_08]: full third floor under the gables, which is cool and unique.

133
00:11:07,839 --> 00:11:18,702
[SPEAKER_08]: That's the Victorian era pushing the limits of architectural construction because they literally have a floor that's being supported by the roof trusses that run down.

134
00:11:19,742 --> 00:11:24,444
[SPEAKER_08]: Then they incorporate all these different mishmashes of things attached to it.

135
00:11:24,464 --> 00:11:31,426
[SPEAKER_08]: They have a rear L, they have a front and side bay, off-center projections.

136
00:11:34,542 --> 00:11:43,644
[SPEAKER_05]: The other thing I noticed about this house is the dormers break the E lane line, which is, I don't see that much in Medford.

137
00:11:44,004 --> 00:11:53,685
[SPEAKER_08]: No, and you often find with these littler buildings that because they're smaller, they can get more ambitious in their architectural detail.

138
00:11:53,765 --> 00:11:58,226
[SPEAKER_08]: So the bigger the building is, the more that person has to spend on money.

139
00:11:58,286 --> 00:12:00,406
[SPEAKER_08]: So in this case, they had tiny areas.

140
00:12:00,426 --> 00:12:02,387
[SPEAKER_08]: So they put the details in like the front porch.

141
00:12:02,427 --> 00:12:03,227
[SPEAKER_08]: And maybe this had,

142
00:12:03,827 --> 00:12:04,707
[SPEAKER_08]: more detail.

143
00:12:04,747 --> 00:12:15,830
[SPEAKER_08]: It looks like it's probably been recited once in its lifetime probably, but, you know, it still resonates in terms of its massing and detail.

144
00:12:16,990 --> 00:12:28,232
[SPEAKER_08]: You know, you might actually find that the original detail is probably still intact and they may have just gone over it, which was the case of 17 Edwards where they just applied a siding over the original.

145
00:12:28,252 --> 00:12:28,293
[SPEAKER_08]: So,

146
00:12:32,124 --> 00:12:34,486
[SPEAKER_08]: You know, they're rare and diminishing.

147
00:12:34,507 --> 00:12:39,311
[SPEAKER_08]: I think this one's actually in a really good state of preservation.

148
00:12:39,331 --> 00:12:44,737
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't know what the inside looks like, but I would like to probably, you know, maybe we should do a site visit, right?

149
00:12:44,777 --> 00:12:50,143
[SPEAKER_08]: I don't know if the building's occupied, but if it's not occupied and it's just sitting there, maybe it's time we do a site visit again, you know?

150
00:12:51,462 --> 00:12:55,426
[SPEAKER_03]: There are some interior shots, but I think they're from like 2005.

151
00:12:56,046 --> 00:12:58,208
[SPEAKER_03]: They're like 11 on maybe Zillow.

152
00:12:58,449 --> 00:13:01,452
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, I looked for a recent sale and I didn't see anything.

153
00:13:01,512 --> 00:13:02,513
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't think there was one.

154
00:13:02,633 --> 00:13:04,455
[SPEAKER_01]: I think a site visit's a great idea, Ryan.

155
00:13:05,532 --> 00:13:29,822
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, I mean, I might feel differently about this one if we actually had a plan of what they're proposing to do, because it sort of seems like if what they're thinking of is something that actually kind of maintains the character of what's there and sort of builds off of it, like, I totally agree with Jen about the density of that particular neighborhood.

156
00:13:32,389 --> 00:13:38,252
[SPEAKER_03]: It would be great if if whatever those townhouses look like we're actually in keeping with with what's already there.

157
00:13:38,272 --> 00:13:45,597
[SPEAKER_01]: I can so usually what they'll do kit is they'll take existing plans of something they've already done and just redo it.

158
00:13:46,297 --> 00:13:47,198
[SPEAKER_01]: So I would look at.

159
00:13:48,225 --> 00:13:52,907
[SPEAKER_01]: Probably not clearly, but look at Jerome, look at Washington Street.

160
00:13:52,928 --> 00:13:55,229
[SPEAKER_01]: They just did something interesting on Washington Street.

161
00:13:55,249 --> 00:13:58,931
[SPEAKER_01]: 69 Jerome is their project.

162
00:13:59,031 --> 00:14:03,053
[SPEAKER_01]: They're doing two side-by-side townhouses on High Street.

163
00:14:04,113 --> 00:14:12,338
[SPEAKER_01]: Again, I don't know what the width is here, but I would bet what they did, I would bet their project on Washington Street or Jerome.

164
00:14:14,555 --> 00:14:15,497
[SPEAKER_01]: they might replicate.

165
00:14:15,557 --> 00:14:21,789
[SPEAKER_01]: I mean, we can ask Sid, he would probably just tell us, but they usually don't stress too far from something they've already done.

166
00:14:21,809 --> 00:14:25,235
[SPEAKER_07]: Nobody's here from the proponent, the owner or the developer.

167
00:14:26,990 --> 00:14:47,106
[SPEAKER_08]: Looking at the interior photos even though they're dated if they haven't got at the house which judging by the condition of these photos I seem to be in okay condition there are things present from the outside, also present on the inside the door casings moldings the banister the bath dual posts, all the typical things, some radiators.

168
00:14:48,528 --> 00:14:50,690
[SPEAKER_08]: window casings, all those seem to be intact.

169
00:14:50,730 --> 00:14:54,794
[SPEAKER_08]: So I think you'll find that this building is probably in good condition inside and out.

170
00:14:54,954 --> 00:15:02,742
[SPEAKER_08]: They're just simply, it has problems with the roof line and things like that, that they would have to completely demolish.

171
00:15:02,782 --> 00:15:09,809
[SPEAKER_08]: So at that point, you just down to a roof and at that point, you might as well just go all the way, which is why we're facing full demolition at this point.

172
00:15:11,791 --> 00:15:23,136
[SPEAKER_08]: We can certainly ask, well, we can certainly look at the building and see what we think, whether we, you know, think in advance of the next meeting, whether we, you know, what we want to say.

173
00:15:23,576 --> 00:15:27,278
[SPEAKER_08]: So, okay, anything else to add on this one?

174
00:15:28,198 --> 00:15:34,521
[SPEAKER_05]: Only other thing I would add is that I don't think there's anything remarkable about the sheds or the garage.

175
00:15:36,080 --> 00:15:37,922
[SPEAKER_05]: I think it's a cinder block, right?

176
00:15:37,962 --> 00:15:41,086
[SPEAKER_05]: Although it has siding on or sheds kind of siding on the front of that.

177
00:15:41,347 --> 00:15:43,409
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't think it was like a carriage house or anything like that.

178
00:15:43,429 --> 00:15:50,498
[SPEAKER_08]: No, they look like there was an extensive carriage house out in the back of this building at one time, but I think that's all been torn down.

179
00:15:50,518 --> 00:15:51,339
